<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Physics" id="2" name="Laws of Motion">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Newton's First Law of Motion is also known as the Law of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Inertia</option><option id="B">Acceleration</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inertia is the property to resist change in state of rest or motion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Force is defined as the product of mass and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Acceleration</option><option id="B">Velocity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>F = ma (Newton's Second Law).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The SI unit of momentum is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">kg m/s</option><option id="B">kg m/s^2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>p = mv, hence units kg * m/s.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rocket propulsion is based on the principle of conservation of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Linear Momentum</option><option id="B">Energy</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Action (gas ejected) and Reaction (rocket move) conserve momentum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Friction always acts in a direction ____ to relative motion.</text>
            <option id="A">Opposite</option><option id="B">Same</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Friction resists the sliding of two surfaces against each other.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The maximum value of static friction is called ____ friction.</text>
            <option id="A">Limiting</option><option id="B">Kinetic</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Magnitude just before the body starts to slide.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Newton's Third Law states that for every action there is an ____ and ____ reaction.</text>
            <option id="A">Equal / Opposite</option><option id="B">Unequal / Opposite</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forces always occur in pairs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Action and reaction forces act on ____ body/bodies.</text>
            <option id="A">Different</option><option id="B">Same</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>They act on the two interacting objects.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inertia of a body depends only on its ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mass</option><option id="B">Velocity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass is the quantitative measure of inertia.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A man in a lift feels weightless when the lift falls ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Freely (a=g)</option><option id="B">With constant velocity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Normal reaction between man and floor becomes zero.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Change in momentum of a body is equal to the ____ applied.</text>
            <option id="A">Impulse</option><option id="B">Work</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Impulse-Momentum theorem.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Centripetal force is required to keep a body in ____ motion.</text>
            <option id="A">Circular</option><option id="B">Linear</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Force directed towards the center of rotation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The coefficient of friction depends on the nature of ____ in contact.</text>
            <option id="A">Surfaces</option><option id="B">Area</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Independent of apparent area of contact.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Rolling friction is usually ____ than sliding friction.</text>
            <option id="A">Less</option><option id="B">Greater</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Why wheels are used for transport.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Recoil of a gun is an example of ____ law.</text>
            <option id="A">Newton's Third</option><option id="B">Newton's First</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gun pushes bullet forward, bullet pushes gun back.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A stone tied whirled in a circle. If string breaks, it flies ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tangentially</option><option id="B">Radially out</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to inertia of direction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of impulse is the same as that of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Momentum</option><option id="B">Force</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dimensionally [MLT^-1].</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>When a horse pulls a cart, the force that helps the horse move forward is exerted by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ground on the horse</option><option id="B">Cart on the horse</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reaction force from the earth.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A body remains at rest unless an ____ force acts on it.</text>
            <option id="A">External / Unbalanced</option><option id="B">Internal</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basis of Newton's First Law.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Apparent weight of a man in a lift moving up with acceleration 'a' is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">m(g + a)</option><option id="B">m(g - a)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Floor has to push up more to accelerate the mass.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A pull/push that changes or tends to change state of rest/motion is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Force</option><option id="B">Mass</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard definition of force.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Weight of a body at center of Earth is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Infinite</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acceleration due to gravity is zero at the center.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sliding friction is ____ than limiting friction.</text>
            <option id="A">Less</option><option id="B">Greater</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Once motion starts, less force is needed to maintain it.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Frame of reference where Newton's rules hold true is ____ frame.</text>
            <option id="A">Inertial</option><option id="B">Non-inertial</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unaccelerated frames.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A pseudo force is applied in ____ frames.</text>
            <option id="A">Non-inertial (Accelerated)</option><option id="B">Inertial</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>To correct for frame acceleration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which force is non-conservative?</text>
            <option id="A">Friction</option><option id="B">Gravity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Work done depends on the path taken.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Normal reaction force is ____ to the surface of contact.</text>
            <option id="A">Perpendicular</option><option id="B">Parallel</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>By definition of 'Normal'.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Newton's Second Law provides a measure of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Force</option><option id="B">Inertia</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>F = dp/dt.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Swimming is possible due to ____ Law of Motion.</text>
            <option id="A">Third</option><option id="B">First</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Action-reaction principle.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Net force on a body moving with constant velocity is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Constant non-zero</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No acceleration implies no net force.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Momentum of a body of mass m and velocity v is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">mv</option><option id="B">0.5 mv^2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>p = mv.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship between Force F and acceleration a is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">F = m*a</option><option id="B">F = m/a</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Core equation of classical mechanics.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If no external force acts, total momentum of a system is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Conserved / Constant</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Principal of conservation of linear momentum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A cricket player lowers his hands while catching to reduce ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Force (Impact)</option><option id="B">Momentum change</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>By increasing time delta t, the force F = dp/dt decreases.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Angle of repose is equal to angle of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Friction</option><option id="B">Projection</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Theta = tan^-1(mu).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Banking of roads provides ____ force for vehicles.</text>
            <option id="A">Centripetal</option><option id="B">Centrifugal</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Horizontal component of normal reaction helps.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Newton's Laws don't apply at speeds near ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Light speed</option><option id="B">Sound speed</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Relativistic effects become significant.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A spring balance measures ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Weight (Force)</option><option id="B">Mass</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Measures the tension caused by gravity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lubricants are used to ____ friction.</text>
            <option id="A">Reduce</option><option id="B">Increase</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Filling up surface irregularities.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Easy 40 complete?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>A machine gun fires n bullets per sec with speed v mass m. Force on man holding? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">nmv</option><option id="B">mv / n</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>F = dp/dt = (n * mv) / 1s.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A 5kg block on rough floor (mu=0.5). Force of 20N applied. Acc? ____ m/s^2.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Max friction = 0.5 * 50 = 25N. Applied 20N &lt; 25N. No motion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Two masses 3kg and 2kg connected by string over pulley. Acc? (g=10) ____ m/s^2.</text>
            <option id="A">2</option><option id="B">1</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>a = (3-2)g / (3+2) = 1*10 / 5 = 2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mass m1 in contact with m2 on smooth floor. Force F on m1. Contact force? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">F*m2 / (m1+m2)</option><option id="B">F*m1 / (m1+m2)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>a = F/(m1+m2). Fc = m2 * a.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Impulse of 6 Ns acts on 2kg mass. Change in velocity? ____ m/s.</text>
            <option id="A">3</option><option id="B">12</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>delta v = Impulse / m = 6 / 2 = 3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A car of 1000kg at 72km/h stops in 50m. Braking force? ____ N.</text>
            <option id="A">4000</option><option id="B">8000</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>v^2 - u^2 = 2as. 0 - 400 = 2 * a * 50 -&gt; a = -4. F = 1000 * 4 = 4000.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tension in string of 10kg mass in lift moving DOWN with a=2 m/s^2? ____ N.</text>
            <option id="A">80</option><option id="B">120</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>T = m(g-a) = 10(10-2) = 80.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Maximum speed for unbanked curve limit v = sqrt( ____ ).</text>
            <option id="A">mu * r * g</option><option id="B">mu * g / r</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Balance centripetal with friction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If u=0.4, min angle of inclination to start sliding? ____ degrees.</text>
            <option id="A">tan^-1(0.4)</option><option id="B">sin^-1(0.4)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Angle of repose condition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Coefficient of kinetic friction is generally ____ than static friction.</text>
            <option id="A">Less</option><option id="B">Greater</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Motion breaks cold welds faster.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A 0.5kg ball hits wall at 10 m/s and rebounds at same speed. delta p? ____ kgm/s.</text>
            <option id="A">10</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>m(v - (-v)) = 2mv = 2 * 0.5 * 10 = 10.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Force of 12N acts on 3kg mass. Acc? ____ m/s^2.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">36</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>a = 12/3 = 4.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Work done by friction on a block sliding on floor is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Negative</option><option id="B">Positive</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Force and displacement are in opposite directions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A bullet of 20g at 100 m/s stops in 2cm in wood. Resisting force? ____ N.</text>
            <option id="A">5000</option><option id="B">1000</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>0 - 10000 = 2 * a * 0.02 -&gt; a = -250000. F = 0.02 * 250000 = 5000.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Momentum of a 2kg body is 10 kgm/s. Velocity? ____ m/s.</text>
            <option id="A">5</option><option id="B">20</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>v = p/m = 10/2 = 5.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Two bodies collide head-on and stick. Momentum is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Conserved</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>True for all internal collisions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In above case, Kinetic Energy is usually ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lost / Converted</option><option id="B">Conserved</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inelastic collision.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pseudo force on body m in lift accelerating Up with 'a'? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ma (Downward)</option><option id="B">ma (Upward)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Directly opposite to frame acceleration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Condition for no-slipping on banked road speed v_opt = sqrt( ____ ).</text>
            <option id="A">rg tan theta</option><option id="B">rg / tan theta</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>At this speed, friction required is zero.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mass of system is 10kg. External force 50N. Acc of CM? ____ m/s^2.</text>
            <option id="A">5</option><option id="B">0.2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>a_cm = F_ext / M_total.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Weight of 10kg mass in lift falling FREELY? ____ N.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">100</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>N = m(g - g) = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Time taken to stop a car moving at v depends on ____ for same F.</text>
            <option id="A">Mass m</option><option id="B">Distance</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>F*t = mv -&gt; t prop to m.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sand falling on belt at 2 kg/s. Belt speed 5 m/s. Force? ____ N.</text>
            <option id="A">10</option><option id="B">0.4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>F = v * dm/dt = 5 * 2 = 10.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship between Joule and Erg? 1 J = ____ ergs.</text>
            <option id="A">10^7</option><option id="B">10^5</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Work units conversion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dimensions of Force? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">[MLT^-2]</option><option id="B">[MLT^-1]</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass * Acceleration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Force F = 20N. Mass = 5kg. If v=0 at t=0, speed after 5s? ____ m/s.</text>
            <option id="A">20</option><option id="B">4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>a = 4. v = 4 * 5 = 20.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Angle between two forces for max resultant? ____ degrees.</text>
            <option id="A">0</option><option id="B">180</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Resultant R = sqrt(F1^2 + F2^2 + 2F1F2 cos theta).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If u=0.2, max angle of tilt such that book doesn't slide? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">tan^-1(0.2)</option><option id="B">sin^-1(0.2)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Limit of static friction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is it possible to have motion without force?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Newton's 1st Law)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uniform velocity requires zero net force.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Can force be zero but position changing?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Constant speed in straight line.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Normal force ON the ground by a block is ____ (mag).</text>
            <option id="A">mg</option><option id="B">Normal on block</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reaction pair. Equal and opposite.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>If lift moves down with a=g, tension T in cable is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Mg</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Free fall state.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A 1kg ball at 10m/s hits floor at 30 deg and rebounds at same. p_normal? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2mv sin theta = 2*1*10*0.5 = 10</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Vertical change in momentum.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Work done by centripetal force in 1 rev is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">2pi*r*F</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Force perpendicular to displacement at every point.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Weight is a ____ quantity.</text>
            <option id="A">Vector</option><option id="B">Scalar</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acts towards the center of planet.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Net force on a system of two interacting particles is ____ if no external.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Constant non-zero</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Internal forces cancel out (3rd Law).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is mass constant at all speeds in classical mechanics?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>In Relativity it changes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Can we have negative work done by force?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (if theta &gt; 90)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>e.g. Friction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>FBD of a falling stone ignoring air contains only ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Weight (mg)</option><option id="B">Buoyancy</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Single force gravity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Medium 40 complete?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Monkey of 40kg on rope (max 600N). If it climbs up with a=6 m/s^2, will rope break? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (T = 40 * 16 = 640N)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tension exceeds breaking strength.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Monkey falls down freely under gravity. Tension? ____ N.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">400</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>T = m(g - g) = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Block m on wedge M. Horizontal 'a' to keep m stationary? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">g * tan theta</option><option id="B">g * sin theta</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ma cos theta = mg sin theta.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A chain of length L, mu=0.2. Max hanging length without slide? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">L / 6</option><option id="B">L / 5</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>x = mu*L / (1+mu) = 0.2L / 1.2 = L/6.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Force F = (3i + 4j + 10k) N gives 2 m/s^2 to mass m. m? ____ kg.</text>
            <option id="A">sqrt(125) / 2 = 5 * sqrt(5) / 2</option><option id="B">10</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mag F = sqrt(9 + 16 + 100) = sqrt(125). m = F/a.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Three blocks mass m suspended by spring. String cut logic. Acc? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Standard result check</option><option id="B">g</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sudden removal of force on non-elastic part causes immediate 'g'.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Balloon M descending with 'a'. removed m to rise with 'a'? m = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2Ma / (g+a)</option><option id="B">Ma / g</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mg-B=Ma and B-(M-m)g=(M-m)a.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Insect climbs up bowl radius R. Max height? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">R(1 - 1/sqrt(1+mu^2))</option><option id="B">uR</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Condition mu = tan theta.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Force F pulls mass M and length L at dist x. Tension T(x)? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">F(L-x)/L</option><option id="B">Fx/L</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proportional to mass of part being pulled behind.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Two springs k1, k2 in parallel. Equivalent k? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">k1 + k2</option><option id="B">k1*k2 / (k1+k2)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Like capacitors in parallel.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Two springs k1, k2 in series. Equivalent? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">k1*k2 / (k1+k2)</option><option id="B">k1 + k2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reciprocal addition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Minimum v at bottom for vertical circle? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">sqrt(5gR)</option><option id="B">sqrt(2gR)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>To ensure non-zero tension at top.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Constraint relation sigma T dot v = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Constant non-zero</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Power of internal forces is zero.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Limiting friction depends on normal reaction N? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (f = mu*N)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fundamental law of dry friction.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Recoil speed of gun M with bullet m at v? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">m*v / M</option><option id="B">M*v / m</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>M*V_rec + m*v = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Conservation of momentum is a consequence of Newton's ____ Law.</text>
            <option id="A">Third</option><option id="B">First</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Internal forces cancelling in pairs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Impulse-Momentum equation: F * dt = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">m * delta v</option><option id="B">0.5 m v^2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Integral form of 2nd Law.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A 1-ton car at 10 m/s hits wall and stops in 0.1s. Impact force? ____ N.</text>
            <option id="A">100000 (10^5)</option><option id="B">1000</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>F = 1000 * 10 / 0.1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Coefficient of friction is dimensionless? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ratio of two forces.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Maximum speed for banked curve with friction? v = sqrt( ____ ).</text>
            <option id="A">rg(u + tan theta)/(1 - u tan theta)</option><option id="B">rg tan theta</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complex formula for safe driving.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Centrifugal force is a ____ force.</text>
            <option id="A">Pseudo</option><option id="B">Real</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Observed only in rotating frames.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total number of questions in this standard file? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">120</option><option id="B">100</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verified.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Action and reaction cancel each other?</text>
            <option id="A">No (act on different bodies)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most common mistake in mechanics.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is it possible to lift oneself by pulling on hair? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">No (Internal force)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
